A: 
why doesn't it give error just like we get in java code?

The Android system does not enforce unique IDs in the same view tree. It's designed this way to allow multiple views with the same ID in different view trees. This is because the ID is used to find a view in the view hierarchy, and it's possible for a view to be part of multiple view trees.

how does environment decide to which component it needs to invoke?

The environment doesn't decide which component to invoke. It's the developer who uses the findViewById() method to get a reference to a view in the current view hierarchy.

What will happen in such case?

If you have two XML layouts with the same ID in different activities, the findViewById() method will return the view from the last setContentView() call. This is because the view hierarchy is reset every time setContentView() is called, so the views from the previous layout are not available.

how do I get the Dialog to correctly resize itself to display all of the content in the custom View?

You can set the width and height of the dialog using the setLayout() method of the dialog's window. Here's an example:

```java
@Override
public Dialog onCreateDialog(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    // Create the dialog
    AlertDialog.Builder db = new AlertDialog.Builder(getActivity());
    db.setTitle("Test Alert Dialog:");
    db.setView(new myView(getActivity()));
    AlertDialog dialog = db.create();

    // Set the layout of the dialog
    dialog.getWindow().setLayout(ViewGroup.LayoutParams.WRAP_CONTENT, ViewGroup.LayoutParams.WRAP_CONTENT);

    return dialog;
}
```

In this example, the width and height of the dialog are set to wrap the content of the custom view. The width is set to WRAP_CONTENT, which means the dialog will be wide enough to fit the content of the custom view. The height is also set to WRAP_CONTENT, which means the dialog will be tall enough to fit the content of the custom view.

Please note that the setLayout() method should be called before the dialog is displayed. If you call it after the dialog is displayed, it won't have any effect.

